## Overview[](#toc_1)

Apollo enables you to build an integration between the web forms on your own website and the scheduling functionality of its [inbound router](https://knowledge.apollo.io/hc/en-us/articles/17919970244109). Your web forms can serve as a substitute for the intake forms you create when setting up inbound routers.

Continue to collect data from prospects on your website, and then provide them with the ability to easily schedule meetings with your team based on the inbound routers you create in Apollo. This can be accomplished in a single, seamless workflow.

[Back to Top](#top)

## Step 0: Before You Begin[](#toc_2)

The instructions provided in the [Step 1](#step-1-create-an-inbound-router-or-use-an-existing-router) and [Step 2](#step-2-copy-apollo-js-snippet-and-map-fields) sections of this article can be completed by an Apollo admin. Technical skills are not required.

The [Step 3](#step-3-build-your-web-form-integration) instructions require knowledge of HTML and a front-end language like JavaScript, along with access to your website's codebase. If you or your team do not possess those technical skills or access, work with your organization to arrange the necessary help.

[Back to Top](#top)

## Step 1: Create an Inbound Router (or Use an Existing Router)[](#toc_3)

You will map your web form fields to the fields in an Apollo inbound router. Create (or update) an inbound router that includes all of the fields that you want to map to your web form.

If you have already created an inbound router with the fields you want to map, proceed to [Step 2](#step-2-copy-apollo-js-snippet-and-map-fields).

If you do not have an inbound router with the desired fields, please refer to [Create Inbound Routers for Your Meetings](https://knowledge.apollo.io/hc/en-us/articles/17919970244109) to learn how to create or update inbound routers. Then, return to this article and continue with [Step 2](#step-2-copy-apollo-js-snippet-and-map-fields).

[Back to Top](#top)

## Step 2: Copy Apollo JS Snippet and Map Fields[](#toc_4)

With an inbound router created, you can proceed to mapping the fields between your web form and Apollo, and then generating the JavaScript snippet to add to your website.

1.  Launch Apollo and click [**Meetings**](https://app.apollo.io/#/meetings/meeting-types).
2.  Click **Inbound routers**. Find the inbound router you want to use with your web form, and then click **additional options** (...) **Share**. [![Find your inbound router.](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i3.png)](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i3.png)
3.  Click the **Integrate with your website form** tab. Enter the domain(s) where your web form is located, and then press enter on your keyboard to save your domain entries. Apollo does not support trailing slashes, so do not include `/` at the end of your domains.

    You can add up to 5 domains, including subdomains. For example, Apollo integrating web forms on `https://app.apollo.io` and `https://knowledge.apollo.io` would occupy 2 of the 5 available domains. [![Add the domains where your web forms are located.](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i10.png)](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i10.png)

4.  Click the **Form field autofill** toggle if you want Apollo to automatically populate any fields with Apollo data when a user inputs their email address into your form. [![Form field autofill toggle in share router popup](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i11.png)](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i11.png)
5.  Then, click the **Hide autofilled form fields** toggle if you want to streamline the form filling experience for your prospects. Form shortening hides any fields that Apollo autofills from the end user's view. This means that your prospects will only see and need to fill out the fields for which Apollo does not have data. You need to activate the form field autofill toggle to enable this feature. [![Form field autofill toggle in share router popup](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i12.png)](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i12.png)

    Be Mindful

    Please note, Apollo recommends that you use the form field autofill feature with caution. If you don't want to alarm a prospect when a field automatically populates with their data, consider enabling the form field autofill and form shortening features together.

    Please also note that for form autofill and shortening to work, your webform must be structered correctly as per HTML semantics. Make sure you have wrapped all inputs within the form element and assigned relevent label tags. You must also ensure that you map your inbound router fields to your web form fields correctly, as per the following step.

6.  Next, map your inbound router fields to your web form fields. The inbound router fields are already populated, so you only need to enter the corresponding web form field. If an inbound router field allows a prospect to select from multiple options, you should ensure that your web form provides the same options.

    The web form field names entered here **must match** the field names in your code. If there is an `emailaddress` field in the code of your web form, enter that full name, not `email`.

    Once you have mapped all your fields, select **Continue**. [![Enter your website form fields.](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i5.png)](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i5.png)

7.  Apollo generates the JavaScript snippet to add to your website. Click **Copy Code** to add it to your clipboard, and then click **Done** to exit.

    If you are building the rest of the integration on your website, keep the code snippet yourself. Otherwise, send it to the personnel that will complete the integration setup. [![Copy the JavaScript code snippet.](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i2.png)](https://storage.googleapis.com/apollo-public-assets/kb_images/integrate_web_form_meetings/i2.png)


With your code snippet generated, continue to [Step 3](#step-3-build-your-web-form-integration).

